The solstice is always the inverse of the season. Thus summer is joyful and bright, but the summer solstice is tragic and sorrowful. And winter is when death rules over nature, but the winter solstice is the most happy and blessed day of the year. The worst has already ended.

The summer solstice is the Door of Men. We all enter this world through it. The winter solstice is the Door of Gods. When it is time for us to leave the world, most of us will go back out through the Door of Men, but some will exit through the Door of Gods.
As God, Christ entered this world through the Door of Gods.

The summer solstice is identified with St. John the Baptist, "St. John who cries", who precedes Christ. The winter solstice is identified with St. John the Evangelist, who achieved Edenic perfection in life and is thus portrayed androgynously, "St. John who laughs".

Thus, in John 3:30, when St. John the Baptist also says "Joy is mine, and it is now complete. He must increase, but I must decrease.", it also marks the summer solstice, from which onwards the sun and daylight start to decrease with each day.

The fact that a 240 000 000$ budget movie is culturally now exclusively remembered through a fake quote that's not in the actual movie and comes from an image that a guy made in 2 minutes on paint proves that ideas and imagination will always triumph over resources and influence.

You can spend a literal billion dollars on a film franchise, hire writers, designers, etc. and a random guy with a computer can rewrite it by pasting a cool quote over a random screencap from the movie. That's it. He triumphed. He made his vision reality. This is the movie now.

Dr. Ray Peat mentioned that St. John's wort's hypericin compound is structurally similar to emodin (and also both to Viamint K and cycline antibiotics), making St. John's wort sort of Europe's equivalent to Cascara Sagrada. An interesting substance inside an interesting herb imo.

If you google it, lots of pepol seem to be more or less successfully using St. John's wort for mental problems like depression/anxiety type stuff. Peat called hypericin a "system of conjugated electrons" which is basically what the mind is. Probably worth trying. St. John's wort.
